******
[3] Outbreak response
Date: 29 Apr 2010
Source: Polio Eradication Initiative [edited]
<http://www.polioeradication.org/content/general/LatestNews201004.asp#04>


Tajikistan is launching an outbreak response
vaccination activity on [1 May 2010] in the
capital Dushanbe and 6 surrounding districts, as
lab testing confirms that 32 children in the
country have been paralysed by polio. This
response is to be followed by 3 nation-wide
vaccination campaigns, the 1st of which is due to
start on [4 May]. Four million doses of vaccine have arrived in the country.

Genetic sequencing has now determined that the
poliovirus is most closely related to virus from
Uttar Pradesh, India. Countries neighbouring
Tajikistan have lined up protective measures:
Uzbekistan is planning to vaccinate its children
under 5 years of age starting in the last week of
May [2010]; Kyrgyzstan is conducting polio
vaccinations as part of European Immunization
Week; Afghanistan has stepped up surveillance
along its border with Tajikistan and is focusing
staff resources on border provinces during its [2
May 2010] nationwide immunization activity.

WHO and UNICEF are urgently seeking emergency
funding to support the costs of the field
operations and vaccination campaigns. Rotary
International, the US Centers for Disease Control
and Prevention and the UK Department for
International Development have already pledged emergency funding.

The Ministries of Health in Tajikistan and
Uzbekistan are supported in their planning and
implementation by WHO, the US Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention, the United Nations
Childrens Fund (UNICEF), the International
Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent
Societies and other partners in the Global Polio Eradication Initiative.

WHO recommendations for travel to Tajikistan are
the same as for any other polio-infected country
­ immunization or boosting of past immunization.
No further actions or travel restrictions are recommended.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[In the above report (see [2] Eurosurveillance
report], as of 27 Apr 2010, there have been 171
cases of AFP with 12 deaths reported of which 32
had WPV1 isolated. This represents an increase of
51 AFP cases and 2 deaths, with 25 addition
isolates of WPV1 since the 1st report of this
outbreak (see prior ProMED-mail posting
Poliomyelitis - Worldwide (04): Tajikistan,
Uzbekistan susp 20100424.1319). Additional
information since the 1st report on this outbreak
includes genetic sequencing of the WPV1 isolated
from cases as most closely resembling viruses
from Uttar Pradesh India. It has been pointed out
that while Afghanistan is still a polio endemic
country not having interrupted transmission and
sustained the interruption for 3 years, the
northern part of Afghanistan has not had recent
poliovirus transmission, with 7 out of the 8
confirmed cases with onset in 2010 having WPV3
isolated, whereas the virus identified in the
current outbreak in Tajiskistan is WPV1. The
identification of the probable origin of the
virus in Uttar Pradesh, a key endemic area in
India further highlights the ease of travel of
microorganisms (and their hosts), crossing borders silently.

We still await word on the findings of the
investigations on the 3 identified AFP cases in
Uzbekistan, as well as more information on
results of the investigation of the outbreak in
Tajikistan, with possible information on the
silent or not so silent spread of the WPV since December 2009.

For the interactive HealthMap/ProMED map of
Tajikistan, showing borders with neighboring
countries (including Uzbekistan and Afghanistan)
see <http://healthmap.org/r/01f4>. For the
interactive HealthMap/ProMED map of Uttar
Pradesh, India, see
<http://healthmap.org/r/00Hk>. Moving the map
around, one can see that Uttar Pradesh is a
significant distance to the southeast from Tajikistan. - Mod.MPP]
